Open water dive with the Oyster dive school out in Wraysbury lake in Heathrow (http://www.wraysbury.ws/).
From log book:
Lake is cold and very murky after lots of people have been dive training. The silt and algea have really been stirred up.
Visibilit was well over 10m.

Strong wind from the south-west led to 0.5m waves and slightly rough boat ride. Saw turtles on the sheer "wall" around 10m. Apparently the bottom is 40-50m. The current was fairly strong but no as much close to the wall.

No dolphins, thats the name of the nearby restort! Lots of turtles but no whale shark that was seen here. We had to pick up 2 people (Gernan + Filipino) as their boat battery failed. Looks like cheap dive wasn't enough to pay for regular servicing of their boat.

My guage registered 18m at the plane, but using 21m for the pressure group calculation. The plane is an old cessna which was placed to start an artificial reef. Its been there for 25 years so far. No much around the plane, mostly a sandy shelf on which the plane rests.
Camera imploded at 9m by my guage, its rated to 10m. The dive master's computer said it was 11m. I've learnt SPG are not accurate!
Dive with Romy/ Ronny(?). We got up early to see dolphins. It was too rough however. We decided to go and try Pescador as it was good the last time. Yoke saw 3 dolphins in the distance.

We saw boxfish a bright yellow one while at 5m stop. I also saw a blue puffer fish and really unusual "pipe fish" that looked like a lollipop! We came up away from the boat and submerged slightly to cover the distance on the DMs suggestion. This brought me down to 40bar.
Heavy rain and waves accompanied our entry into the water. The locals though it was really cold. I told them 25 was the best possible summer in Ireland!
http://www.divesitedirectory.co.uk/dive_site_uk_england_southwest_reefs_mewstone_ridges.html

There were a few dive boats here and divers doing deco. stops on the shot line. Graham Nash came with us to float as Patrick isn't yet a Sports Diver.
The wreck/artificial reef was interesting. I came down the shot line to the bridge. There was a big hold cut in the roof and I went in to get a few shots. The Scylla has been under the water now for 6+ years and there lots of life start to cling all over it. The deepest point I got to was when we drifted over the side at one point, which put us at 18.6m. The hull goes down to 24m although we didn't do this.
I had difficulty with boyancy here. I wasn't able to hold a stop at 8m. I think I was coming up faster then I couldn't dump air fast enough. Just to be safe I didn't go on the second dive of the day.
http://www.divesitedirectory.co.uk/dive_site_uk_england_southwest_wreck_hms_scylla.html

Dicky found a snow crab here hiding amoungst the Kelp and ridges. The tide was starting to come in. The cox noticed there was a peak rising up from 9m to 2m which we all entered the water around. The GPS for it is on the boat computer.

This dive contains three caves in a reef wall. The current was very strong, the strongest I've experienced so far. Had to haul myself down the shot line. There were lots of fish hidding in nooks and crannies in the reef. We saw trumpet fish, red snappers, angel fish, conger eel. DM brought us back to shot line, however not directly after we indicated 100 and then 50 bar. This resulted in Yoke have to buddy breath at 5m. I was down to 20bar. The current got stronger while trying to hold 3min stop at 5min. The shot line snapped and we were whisked to the surface. The DM said these were the worst conditions he'd seen in years. Stressful dive with terrible visibility. I was quite unhappy with DM as we should have started back earlier or came up and not got to the air sharing situation.

Much calmer dive with a smaller current. Dived down the shot line to 20m. The visibility wasn't much better. We swam the reef overhang at the bottom. Lots of fish were hiding in cracks. Got a great shot of a nudibranch with the aid of the DM's LED torch. We ascended to 15m to swim a long the top of reef and back towards the shot line. I was still too low on air getting to the surface then I would have liked.
We were going to see the where thresher and other sharks eat. This meant wait around at 25-30m to see if any would show up. It was dark and cold
Saw thresher shark and accidentally decensed to 38m while filming with gopro...

Jumped from the boat dive platform. Followed line to reef. Went along until ~120bar with reef on right hand side. The headed back and moved up to ~10m. Did 3@5m while watching the "cleaning station" action near on of the mooring lines the boat used.
GoPro rollback, numida wreck, yoke free flow, yoke buddy breath, nice coral and fish on wreck super structure.
Dived down at rear. Saw big open rear doors. didn't go in. swam around the "top deck" to the front then up partially open front bow. Continued up the side and finished at the shot line with 3@5m.

This was a training dive for Sports Diver course. The first dive involved navigating by compass and doing a reciprocal route. I then put up the DSMB and we then pottered about. It was very poor visibility. It was my first time diving with the dive knife. One strap came loose. Dicky managed to save it from getting lost. Things nearly went pear shapped as air ran to my feet trying to remove the knife's remaining strap to my leg while I tried to hold on to the DSMB. We got it sorted out in the end.

This was a quick dive to practive swimming with a distance line. 20 strokes out and back. The I had to do a CBL (Control Boyant Lift) practice on Dicky. Once reaching the surface I then had to do rescue breathing and towing back to shore. Dicky kindly help on to his own mask rather then have it lost.

First dive with Cannon D5 in its Nauticam enclosure. 40min before the dive I set up the leak detection system and let it sit. It held the green light through out the dive. We did a stride entry from a hard boat. The camera was passed in after entry. 8kg was too little and the DM gave me and extra 3kg to get down. Saw sea snakes however there wasn't much in the way of fish.

First dive with Cannon D5 in its Nauticam enclosure. 40min before the dive I set up the leak detection system and let it sit. It held the green light through out the dive. We did a stride entry from a hard boat. The camera was passed in after entry. 8kg was too little and the DM gave me and extra 3kg to get down. Saw sea snakes however there wasn't much in the way of fish.

We helped film a wedding propsal for two people we met. This was a shore dive from the Harbour. The wet socks had no grip on the slipway so we did a stride entry from the end of the pier which was 3m drop to the water. There were a lot of nudibranch around and there was also a sea cave, It was a good dive to finish on.

First dive of the year at sea in a dry suit. I had problems getting down and then holding the 3 @ 5m. I borrowed an extra 2Kg from James Fleet for later dives. The visibility wasn't great although we did see a lot of different things. Snow crabs, a dog fish, wrass to name a few. There was much more life about this time then my last dive here. It was a good dive all in all.
Plankton bloom obscured most of the wreck. We were also experiencing current as we weren't diving at slack tide. It would later turn out we hadn't got the right times.
We got dragged by the current away to deeper water and the depth increased. We were unable to swim back and so aborted the dive early. The visibility wasn't bad near the pinacles of rock.
The slack was around 10am according to InDeep dive centre and was indeed quite calm when I got in. I was
Diving as a three
The clearest I've ever seen the Scylla at about 8m visibility.
Found the boilers Small schools of fish
Wreck
Strong current pulling us south west. Saw black and yellow nudibranch. Lots of sea urchins, got spiked by one. Not a great dive

Strong winds blowing up to 17mph. The dive center has a pier inside a lago. you have to cross a reef to get out to the dive sites. The waves after the lagoon were big and the roll was very unpleasant (got sick while boat picked up others). The dive visibility was ~10m+ not as good as it can be due to the weather. Today was the first time the dive center did diving since 22nd December!
On the dive saw giant lobster, crab, big baracoda and in this distance what i thought was a big nepolean wrass in a school of fish. Even at 15m there was a bit of a roll/swell.

The wind direction changed today so it appeared calmer. However beyond the reef and out to sea it was still big rollers. I hadn't any breakfast, just coffee and a snack bar. The dive itself was deeper and clearer maybe 15m+ visibility. Even at 20m there was still swell between the cayon "fingers" we saw above and around. Lots more to see, clown fish and nurse shark and lots of soft coral.

Couldn't equalise my ear, had head cold and had to give up and go back to the boat. I then spent an hour rolling around trying not to throw up. I forgot to bring hat, so had to wrap gear back around my head to ward off the sun, which worked. This trip was truly terrible.

Dived with SLR and large tank from dive magic. This was equivalent to 15l i think but was a massive heavy aluminium tank. This was a wall dive with strong current. We saw turtle and bigger fish however the current was strong so there was no stopping.

Dived with SLR and large tank from dive magic. This was equivalent to 15l i think but was a massive heavy aluminium tank. This was a nice reef dive with strong current. We are dropped onto the sandy bottom first to approach the reef and potentially see rays, which we didn't this time.

Dived with profondo and their hard boat. It was very well organised with allocated back and hanger space on the boat (I was number 38). Noticeable thermocline after ~13m, felt quite cold and remained so until you came up above it. Saw octopus which was amazing and nudibranch with lots of sea grass. I used gopro with new bottom light mount.

Wind had picked up and we went out of the harbour and left fallowing the cliff around to shelter. Swell/roll was ~+/-0.5m. Noticeable thermocline after ~13m, felt quite cold and remained so until you came up above it.Dived small cave under the guidance of Alex, came out and saw lots of nudibranch, schools of sardnines and small dancer fish which two large jacks hunted on two occasions. The visibility was somewhat reduced as the weather is going to be bad tomorrow 19th.
